WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:11.720
Hi from Tokyo Japan, and welcome to Jeremy’s&nbsp;
IT Lab. In this video we’re going to cover REST&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.720 --> 00:00:18.040
API authentication. We’ve already covered the&nbsp;
basics of REST APIs, but Cisco recently added&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:24.160
authentication to the list of things you need&nbsp;
to know about REST for the CCNA exam. APIs give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:29.720
access to an application and its data, so security&nbsp;
should always be a major concern when designing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.720 --> 00:00:36.640
and using APIs. In this video, we’ll examine&nbsp;
some common methods of REST API authentication.

00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:41.880
But before we get started, let me take a minute&nbsp;
to shill my books, Acing the CCNA Exam volumes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:47.240
1 and 2. These books are up to date, covering&nbsp;
everything you need for the latest version of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:54.520
the exam. REST API authentication, for example,&nbsp;
is covered in chapter 23 of volume 2. I highly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.520 --> 00:00:59.000
recommend using books in combination with&nbsp;
a video course, and if you want my books,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:04.640
you can get them at the links on the screen&nbsp;
now, or on Amazon. Now let’s get started.

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:09.000
So, what are we going to cover in this&nbsp;
video? First, I’ll introduce the concept&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.880
of REST API authentication in general,&nbsp;
including why it’s so important. Then,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.880 --> 00:01:18.440
for the rest of the video, we’ll cover&nbsp;
four common types of REST authentication:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:25.840
basic authentication, bearer authentication,&nbsp;
API key authentication, and finally OAuth2.0.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:31.600
We’ll outline how each of these methods works,&nbsp;
and their advantages and disadvantages. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:36.880
that’s the plan for today. Now let’s&nbsp;
learn about REST API authentication.

00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:41.120
Hopefully you already know this definition&nbsp;
from the security section of the course, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:46.600
authentication is the process of validating the&nbsp;
identity of a user or system to ensure legitimate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:53.600
access to resources. In the case of an API, the&nbsp;
resource is the application and its data. In many&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:59.320
cases, these resources should be protected. But&nbsp;
without authentication, unauthorized users can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:06.280
send API requests, potentially accessing sensitive&nbsp;
data or modifying the application. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:12.560
here we have an application and some data. The API&nbsp;
serves as an interface, allowing other apps to use&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.560 --> 00:02:18.720
the application or to access its data. Without&nbsp;
authentication, if a malicious user sends an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:26.200
API call, also called an API request, the API will&nbsp;
accept the request and provide the requested data.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:32.040
It’s worth noting that some APIs are intentionally&nbsp;
open and don’t require authentication. These APIs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:38.480
typically provide publicly available data&nbsp;
that doesn’t require security protection.

00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:43.960
But for many APIs, that isn’t the case,&nbsp;
and security is a major concern. When the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:49.160
malicious user makes the API call, the API&nbsp;
should authenticate the user, asking “who&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:55.400
are you?”. If the authentication process fails,&nbsp;
the request is denied and the user doesn’t get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.400 --> 00:03:01.240
access to the data. Implementing a reliable&nbsp;
authentication method like this is essential&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:06.880
for protecting applications and data that aren’t&nbsp;
meant to be publicly available. And in addition to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:13.440
security concerns, many APIs track usage for&nbsp;
analytics and billing purposes. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:19.840
charging customers according to how much they use&nbsp;
the API is a common practice. A great example is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:27.880
the ChatGPT API. Many AI applications use ChatGPT&nbsp;
behind the scenes, and OpenAI charges businesses&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:34.080
based on token usage. Basically, a token&nbsp;
is a chunk of text, either input or output,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:41.400
and this means companies pay more as they send&nbsp;
larger or more frequent requests to the API.

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:46.880
So, to summarize the previous slide, when working&nbsp;
with REST APIs, authentication is crucial for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:54.000
verifying a client’s identity and securing access&nbsp;
to resources. REST APIs use various types of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:59.920
authentication to achieve this, and we’ll cover&nbsp;
some key ones in this video. These authentication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:59.920 --> 00:04:05.000
types are also called authentication methods,&nbsp;
or authentication schemes; those are the more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:11.160
technical terms. In this video, we’re going to&nbsp;
cover four of them. The first method is basic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:17.720
authentication. As the name suggests, this is the&nbsp;
simplest form of REST authentication. It sends a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:24.640
username and password in every request, encoded&nbsp;
in Base64 format. Note that encoding is not the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:32.120
same as encryption; I’ll explain that in the next&nbsp;
slide. Next, we have bearer authentication. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.120 --> 00:04:37.800
method uses a token, called a bearer token,&nbsp;
included as an HTTP header in the request,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.800 --> 00:04:43.800
to verify the client’s identity. This method&nbsp;
is quite common in modern APIs; the client&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:50.520
first obtains a token and then includes it in&nbsp;
requests after that. Another common method is API&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:56.920
key authentication. This requires a unique key,&nbsp;
which is typically included as an HTTP header,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.920 --> 00:05:03.160
like the bearer token. The API key acts as a&nbsp;
unique identifier for the client, and is useful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:10.480
for tracking usage. Finally, we have OAuth 2.0.&nbsp;
This is a more advanced and secure authentication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:18.320
framework that grants access using access tokens.&nbsp;
OAuth 2.0 is widely used for delegated access&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:24.000
and third-party authentication. I’ll break down&nbsp;
what those terms mean when we cover OAuth 2.0 in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:31.400
detail. But if you’ve ever seen the “log in with&nbsp;
google” option on a website, that’s OAuth2.0. Each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.400 --> 00:05:39.280
of these methods has its own advantages and&nbsp;
use cases. Now let’s look at them one by one.

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:44.440
We’ll start with basic authentication, which&nbsp;
authenticates using a username and password in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.440 --> 00:05:51.040
the HTTP headers of each API request. Before&nbsp;
we dive deeper into basic authentication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:55.720
let's first break down the structure of an HTTP&nbsp;
message so you can see where authentication fits&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.720 --> 00:06:02.360
in. It begins with what’s called the start line,&nbsp;
which includes three pieces of information: The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:02.360 --> 00:06:12.880
HTTP method, which is POST in this case; the URL,&nbsp;
which is api/v1/acl/rules; and the HTTP version,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:18.840
which is 2 in this case. The POST method&nbsp;
is typically used for a create operation;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:24.600
think back to the CRUD operations (create, read,&nbsp;
update, delete) we covered in the previous video&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.600 --> 00:06:32.680
on REST. So, this HTTP message is probably a&nbsp;
request to create something on the server. Next,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:32.680 --> 00:06:38.960
we have the headers. These provide metadata about&nbsp;
the request, such as authentication details,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:44.000
content type, and information about the&nbsp;
client making the request. Often there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.040
are several headers; there are four in this&nbsp;
case. The headers are followed by a blank line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:56.280
and then there is the message body, the actual&nbsp;
contents of the message. This is the HTTP message,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.280 --> 00:07:01.760
which would then be encapsulated in a TCP&nbsp;
segment to be sent over the network. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:06.560
message is using basic authentication;&nbsp;
can you find it? It’s this line right&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:11.280
here. It uses the “Authorization” header,&nbsp;
but the real purpose is to authenticate the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.280 --> 00:07:18.360
request. And then that authentication can&nbsp;
be used to provide proper authorization.

00:07:18.360 --> 00:07:22.800
Now that we’ve identified where the basic&nbsp;
authentication occurs in the HTTP headers of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:29.520
the API request, let’s look a bit deeper at basic&nbsp;
authentication. As I said, basic authentication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:35.960
includes a username and password in the HTTP&nbsp;
headers. These credentials are encoded in Base64&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:42.880
format, but not encrypted. That’s an important&nbsp;
distinction. Base64 is an encoding scheme,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:48.880
which is simply a way of representing data.&nbsp;
And unlike encryption, it is not secure and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.880 --> 00:07:54.640
can be easily decoded. So, although I’ve been&nbsp;
referring to HTTP, you really should be using&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:54.640 --> 00:08:03.640
HTTPS with your REST APIs for security. HTTPS&nbsp;
is HTTP plus TLS, Transport Layer Security,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:09.200
which provides robust encryption and security.&nbsp;
The username and password used for basic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:17.240
authentication are sent in the format username&nbsp;
colon password, encoded in Base64. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:24.400
username jeremy and password ccna would be sent&nbsp;
as this string of characters. If you’re curious,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:32.280
you can visit this URL, base64decode.org,&nbsp;
to encode and decode base64. So, let’s see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.280 --> 00:08:37.560
how basic authentication works in action.&nbsp;
On the right here we have the REST server,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.560 --> 00:08:43.240
with an API allowing access to its data. And&nbsp;
on the left we have a client app that wants&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:48.720
to access the data. It sends an API call,&nbsp;
including the “Authorization” header for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.720 --> 00:08:55.440
authentication. Notice the password is encoded&nbsp;
in Base64; that’s username jeremy and password&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.440 --> 00:09:03.360
ccna. The authentication succeeds, so the server&nbsp;
grants the request and responds with the data. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:08.080
it’s that simple: a username and password are&nbsp;
included with each request, and if they’re&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:14.240
correct, authentication succeeds. Now that&nbsp;
we’ve seen how basic authentication works,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:20.560
let’s consider the advantages and disadvantages.&nbsp;
Honestly, the main advantage is that it’s simple&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:20.560 --> 00:09:26.080
and easy to implement, just a username and&nbsp;
password. But since those credentials are sent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:31.760
in every request, attackers could steal them if&nbsp;
the connection isn’t properly secured. But really,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:36.920
that applies for any authentication method:&nbsp;
HTTPS is essential when communicating over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:44.000
the modern Internet; you shouldn’t use regular&nbsp;
HTTP. But even if using HTTPS for encryption,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:49.400
relying solely on a username and password&nbsp;
combination isn’t particularly secure. If an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:54.600
attacker gets access to the credentials, whether&nbsp;
through social engineering or another attack,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.600 --> 00:10:03.200
they get access to the API. So that’s basic&nbsp;
authentication. Let’s move on to the next method.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:07.840
Next, we’ll look at bearer authentication,&nbsp;
which is a form of token-based authentication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:13.240
and uses a token instead of a username&nbsp;
and password. In bearer authentication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:13.240 --> 00:10:18.600
the client first obtains a token by authenticating&nbsp;
with an authorization server, often just called an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:23.520
“auth server”. This is typically different from&nbsp;
the server actually hosting the resource the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.520 --> 00:10:29.320
client wants to access. Note that authenticating&nbsp;
with the auth server can be done using basic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:29.320 --> 00:10:35.040
authentication or another authentication method.&nbsp;
This step is separate from the actual API request&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:41.640
to the resource server. Then, after the client&nbsp;
gets the token, for each API request, the client&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:47.240
includes the token in the HTTP authorization&nbsp;
header like we saw before. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:47.240 --> 00:10:52.920
it will look something like this: Authorization:&nbsp;
Bearer, and then the token. Let’s see how it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:52.920 --> 00:10:58.800
works. Notice I’m showing two servers now. One&nbsp;
is the auth server, which generates the token.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:58.800 --> 00:11:05.240
And then the resource server, which hosts whatever&nbsp;
resource the client wants to access. So, to begin,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:10.360
the client requests a token from the auth server,&nbsp;
and if successful, the server grants the client&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:16.800
a token. Then, when the client sends an API call&nbsp;
to the resource server, it includes the token in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.800 --> 00:11:23.080
the call. And then the resource server responds,&nbsp;
either with the requested resource, or a message&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:29.240
indicating the server did what was requested. So,&nbsp;
that’s basically how bearer authentication works.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:35.760
The term “bearer” means that anyone who possesses&nbsp;
the token can use it. This means that, if an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:42.200
attacker steals the token, they can make requests,&nbsp;
API calls, as if they were the legitimate user.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:47.480
This is clearly a security problem, so to&nbsp;
mitigate against this, tokens usually expire&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.480 --> 00:11:54.040
after a set period of time. The expiration time&nbsp;
depends on the API’s security needs. Some tokens&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:59.840
expire in 15 minutes to reduce risk, while&nbsp;
others last weeks or months for convenience,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:05.840
especially in low-security environments. Okay,&nbsp;
let’s summarize by considering some advantages&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:12.600
and disadvantages of bearer authentication. First&nbsp;
off, it’s more secure than basic authentication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.600 --> 00:12:16.680
because there’s no need to transmit the same&nbsp;
username and password for every single API&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:16.680 --> 00:12:23.920
call. The tokens that are used instead expire, so&nbsp;
a stolen token will only be temporarily valid. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:28.560
still, it’s worth mentioning as a disadvantage&nbsp;
that, if the token is stolen, the attacker can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.560 --> 00:12:35.400
still access the API until the token expires. And&nbsp;
since tokens need to be refreshed periodically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:39.720
it adds some extra complexity when implementing&nbsp;
bearer authentication, compared to basic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:39.720 --> 00:12:44.280
authentication. That’s not a problem for&nbsp;
network engineers, but for the programmers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:50.520
who build these APIs it’s worth considering.&nbsp;
And finally, just like basic authentication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:57.440
it should only be used with HTTPS. If the token is&nbsp;
sent in cleartext, no encryption, it simply isn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.440 --> 00:13:04.440
secure; you need HTTPS when communicating over the&nbsp;
modern internet. While bearer tokens are commonly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:13.320
used for user authentication in APIs, some APIs&nbsp;
use a simpler method, which we’ll cover next.

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:20.560
Next up is API key authentication, which uses a&nbsp;
static key issued by the API provider. The client&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:20.560 --> 00:13:26.840
uses this key in each API call for authentication.&nbsp;
The main difference between a bearer token and a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:33.160
key is that, unlike bearer tokens, the API key&nbsp;
is static. It doesn’t expire automatically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:39.560
so it remains valid until revoked. API keys&nbsp;
can be sent to the server in a few ways.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:39.560 --> 00:13:45.480
The recommended way is to include the key in the&nbsp;
HTTP Authorization header, as we saw in basic and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:45.480 --> 00:13:50.920
bearer authentication. But you can also include&nbsp;
the key in the URL, in the start line of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:58.360
HTTP request, by adding a parameter to the URL.&nbsp;
But this is not recommended for several reasons,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:03.880
one being that since URLs are often logged&nbsp;
by web servers, proxies, and browsers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.880 --> 00:14:11.640
API keys included in URLs can be exposed in logs,&nbsp;
making them vulnerable to attackers. And a third&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:17.920
option is to send the API key as a cookie, which&nbsp;
is sometimes used for browser-based APIs. But in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:17.920 --> 00:14:23.160
any case, the recommended method is to include&nbsp;
the key in the authorization header. Let’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:28.080
see what it looks like; it’s quite simple.&nbsp;
The client sends an API call to the server&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:33.680
hosting the resource it wants to access. And the&nbsp;
client includes the API key in the authorization&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:33.680 --> 00:14:41.760
header of the HTTP message. Assuming the key was&nbsp;
valid, the server then sends its response. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:48.120
now that we’ve seen how it works, let’s consider&nbsp;
a couple of advantages and disadvantages. One&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:54.320
advantage is that it’s easier to implement than&nbsp;
Bearer authentication. And API key authentication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:54.320 --> 00:15:00.600
is good for tracking usage. The API provider can&nbsp;
assign a unique key to each customer, and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.600 --> 00:15:07.400
easily track each customer’s usage by tracking&nbsp;
the key used in each API call. Because of this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:07.400 --> 00:15:14.040
API keys are often used in cloud services and&nbsp;
third-party APIs. If you’re wondering what a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:14.040 --> 00:15:20.520
third-party API is, think of a developer that&nbsp;
builds a chatbot app that uses ChatGPT. The end&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:26.640
users are the first party. The developer creating&nbsp;
the chatbot app is the second party. But instead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:33.720
of generating responses itself, the app calls&nbsp;
OpenAI’s API to get responses from ChatGPT.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:33.720 --> 00:15:39.080
Since OpenAI is external to both the users and&nbsp;
the app developer, it’s the third party in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:39.080 --> 00:15:46.200
interaction. Hopefully that makes sense! Now let’s&nbsp;
look at a couple of disadvantages. One problem is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:53.040
that, if stolen, the key grants full access until&nbsp;
revoked. It doesn’t automatically expire. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:53.040 --> 00:15:58.240
API keys must be rotated manually to maintain&nbsp;
security, whereas the tokens used in bearer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:58.240 --> 00:16:07.040
authentication expire automatically. Okay&nbsp;
that’s all for API key authentication.

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:13.200
Finally, we move on to OAuth 2.0. It’s a secure&nbsp;
authentication framework that is widely used in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:18.480
modern web applications. Its overall purpose is&nbsp;
different from the other methods we’ve looked at,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:23.480
in that it provides access delegation,&nbsp;
granting third-party applications limited&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:23.480 --> 00:16:28.920
access to resources on behalf of the resource’s&nbsp;
owner. The main benefit is that there is no need&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:28.920 --> 00:16:34.780
to share the resource owner’s credentials with&nbsp;
the third party. For example, when you use ‘Log&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.780 --> 00:16:40.480
in with Google’ on a website, the website&nbsp;
never sees your Google password. Instead,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:40.480 --> 00:16:46.360
Google confirms your identity and grants&nbsp;
access only to approved information. Let’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:46.360 --> 00:16:53.040
look at some examples of OAuth2.0. The first is&nbsp;
what I just mentioned, logging in with google.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:58.280
Many websites and apps offer the option to log&nbsp;
in using your Google account. The third party&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:58.280 --> 00:17:03.680
website or app is granted access to some of your&nbsp;
Google account’s information, without actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:03.680 --> 00:17:09.120
getting access to your account’s credentials.&nbsp;
Connecting apps to social media accounts is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:09.120 --> 00:17:17.000
another example. Many apps can be connected to&nbsp;
Instagram, Facebook, LinkedIn, etc. OAuth 2.0&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:22.960
lets these apps access your social media account&nbsp;
for specific tasks, like posting on your behalf,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:28.960
without revealing your login credentials.&nbsp;
Calendar integration is one more example.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:28.960 --> 00:17:34.920
A third-party tool, like a scheduling app, can&nbsp;
be given access to your Google calendar to check&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:41.280
availability and schedule meetings. These are&nbsp;
all common examples of OAuth2.0. Now let’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:47.240
see how it actually works. There are four main&nbsp;
parties involved. First is the resource owner,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:47.240 --> 00:17:53.280
the account owner granting access to their data.&nbsp;
Using the Google calendar integration example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:53.280 --> 00:17:58.840
this is the owner of the google account. Next&nbsp;
is the client app, the third-party application&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:59.440 --> 00:18:06.000
requesting access to your Google data, like a&nbsp;
scheduling tool accessing your calendar. Then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:11.360
there is the auth server. This server issues&nbsp;
access tokens, granting limited access to your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:18.680
google account, after receiving user approval.&nbsp;
In this example, this is Google’s OAuth service.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:23.560
Finally, there is the resource server, the&nbsp;
server that hosts the protected resource. In&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:28.760
this example, it’s the server hosting the Google&nbsp;
calendar data that the client app wants to access.

00:18:31.640 --> 00:18:38.840
Now let’s see OAuth2.0 in action. The overall&nbsp;
process consists of six main steps. First,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:38.840 --> 00:18:43.720
the client app requests authorization&nbsp;
from the resource owner. In our example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:43.720 --> 00:18:49.040
this could be a scheduling app requesting&nbsp;
access to your Google Calendar. Next,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:54.200
the resource owner—which is you, the account&nbsp;
owner—grants authorization by logging into your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:54.200 --> 00:18:58.720
Google account and giving permission for the&nbsp;
scheduling app to access your calendar data.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:04.600
Once permission is granted, the client app&nbsp;
exchanges this authorization grant for an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:04.600 --> 00:19:11.080
access token from the auth server—which in this&nbsp;
case, is Google’s OAuth service. The auth server&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:11.080 --> 00:19:17.160
then issues an access token to the client app.&nbsp;
This token acts as a temporary key that allows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:17.160 --> 00:19:23.680
the app to request resources on your behalf. Now&nbsp;
that the client app has a token, it includes the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:23.680 --> 00:19:28.840
token in an API request to the resource server,&nbsp;
which hosts the actual data—in this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.840 --> 00:19:35.440
your Google Calendar data. Finally, the resource&nbsp;
server validates the access token and provides the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:35.440 --> 00:19:41.040
requested resource back to the client app. If&nbsp;
the token is valid and the app has the correct&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:41.040 --> 00:19:47.600
permissions, it will receive the data it needs.&nbsp;
The key part of OAuth 2.0 is the access token&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:47.600 --> 00:19:54.080
issued in step 4. It functions like the tokens we&nbsp;
saw in bearer authentication. It grants access to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:54.080 --> 00:20:00.720
the specified resource within the allowed scope,&nbsp;
for example read-only access. And just as in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:00.720 --> 00:20:07.520
bearer authentication, access tokens expire after&nbsp;
a short period, which helps improve security. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:07.520 --> 00:20:12.560
instead of requiring the user to log in again&nbsp;
every single time the access token expires,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:12.560 --> 00:20:18.920
OAuth 2.0 uses refresh tokens, granted by the auth&nbsp;
server, which allow the client app to request a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:18.920 --> 00:20:25.280
new access token without user interaction. This&nbsp;
way, the app can maintain access over an extended&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:32.560
period of time without constantly requiring the&nbsp;
user to log in. So, that’s OAuth 2.0. It allows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:32.560 --> 00:20:37.840
third-party apps to securely access a user’s&nbsp;
data without exposing their credentials, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:37.840 --> 00:20:44.200
while allowing users to control what information&nbsp;
is shared. That’s why OAuth 2.0 is so widely used&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:44.200 --> 00:20:52.440
in modern web applications. By the way, OAuth&nbsp;
2.0 is defined in RFC 6749, which you can access&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:52.440 --> 00:20:59.640
from this link here, or just google search for&nbsp;
RFC 6749. Diving into RFCs isn’t expected for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:59.640 --> 00:21:07.760
the CCNA exam, but if you’re curious to learn&nbsp;
more about OAuth 2.0, it’s worth checking out.

00:21:07.760 --> 00:21:12.040
Alright, let’s wrap things up with a quick summary&nbsp;
of what we covered in this video before we move on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:12.040 --> 00:21:18.760
to the quiz. REST API authentication ensures that&nbsp;
only authorized users or systems can access an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:18.760 --> 00:21:26.320
API. Without it, anyone could send API requests,&nbsp;
potentially exposing or modifying sensitive data.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:32.640
We looked at four types of REST API authentication&nbsp;
methods. Basic Authentication uses a username and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:32.640 --> 00:21:38.520
password encoded in Base64, but it’s not&nbsp;
encrypted, so it must be used with HTTPS&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:38.520 --> 00:21:44.200
for security. Actually, that statement really&nbsp;
applies to all of these authentication methods:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:44.200 --> 00:21:51.480
in the modern internet, you should always use&nbsp;
HTTPS, not regular HTTP. Bearer Authentication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:51.480 --> 00:21:56.560
is a step up in security, using a token&nbsp;
issued by an authorization server instead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:56.560 --> 00:22:02.480
of sending a username and password in every&nbsp;
request. Tokens expire after a short time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:02.480 --> 00:22:09.640
which increases security, but they can still&nbsp;
be stolen if not protected with HTTPS. Next,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:09.640 --> 00:22:16.520
API Key Authentication works similarly but uses a&nbsp;
static key issued by the API provider. It’s good&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.520 --> 00:22:23.960
for tracking API usage, so it’s commonly used by&nbsp;
cloud service providers and third-party APIs. It’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:23.960 --> 00:22:28.960
easier to implement than bearer authentication,&nbsp;
but it’s considered less secure because stolen&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:28.960 --> 00:22:35.400
keys remain valid until manually revoked.&nbsp;
They don’t automatically expire. Finally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:35.400 --> 00:22:41.560
OAuth 2.0 is a framework for access delegation,&nbsp;
allowing third-party applications limited access&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:41.560 --> 00:22:47.720
to a user’s resources without sharing login&nbsp;
credentials. It relies on access tokens that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:47.720 --> 00:22:52.000
can be refreshed with a refresh token,&nbsp;
allowing continued access without user&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:59.000
reauthentication. OAuth 2.0 involves four&nbsp;
key parties: the resource owner, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:04.360
the owner of the Google account. The client&nbsp;
app, the app that requests access to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:04.360 --> 00:23:10.280
account’s resources. The authorization server,&nbsp;
which grants the client app a token to provide&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:10.280 --> 00:23:16.040
limited access to the requested resource. And&nbsp;
finally, the resource server; the server that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:16.040 --> 00:23:22.280
hosts the protected resource: for example, the&nbsp;
Google account’s information. Okay, that’s what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:28.440
we covered in the video. Now let’s move on&nbsp;
to a quick quiz to test your understanding.

00:23:29.240 --> 00:23:34.920
Here’s quiz question 1. Which of the following&nbsp;
REST authentication methods involve an Auth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:34.920 --> 00:23:45.320
server issuing tokens? Select two. Pause&nbsp;
the video now to think about your answers.

00:23:45.320 --> 00:23:51.840
Okay, the answers are A and B, OAuth 2.0 and&nbsp;
bearer authentication. Here’s the diagram I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:51.840 --> 00:23:58.560
showed for OAuth 2.0, and here’s the diagram&nbsp;
for bearer authentication. Basic authentication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:58.560 --> 00:24:04.240
doesn’t involve an auth server; it just uses&nbsp;
simple username and password authentication. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:04.240 --> 00:24:13.520
neither does API key authentication, which uses a&nbsp;
static key. Okay, let’s go to the next question.

00:24:13.520 --> 00:24:17.240
Here’s question 2. Which of the&nbsp;
following best describes how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:17.240 --> 00:24:26.840
OAuth 2.0 improves security? Pause the&nbsp;
video now to think about your answer.

00:24:26.840 --> 00:24:32.200
Okay, the answer is B, it allows third-party&nbsp;
apps to access resources without exposing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:32.200 --> 00:24:38.400
user credentials. Here’s the diagram once again.&nbsp;
Instead of using the resource owner’s credentials&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:44.440
for authentication, the client app receives an&nbsp;
access token from the auth server in step 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:48.120
which allows it to authenticate&nbsp;
with the resource server in step 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:48.120 --> 00:24:56.040
and then access the resource. Okay,&nbsp;
let’s go to the next question.

00:24:56.040 --> 00:24:59.760
Here’s question 3. Which of the&nbsp;
following statements are true?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:59.760 --> 00:25:08.600
Select three. Pause the video&nbsp;
now to think about your answers.

00:25:08.600 --> 00:25:14.480
Okay, the answers are B, C, and E. B is&nbsp;
correct because bearer authentication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:22.520
does require a token; the term “bearer” refers to&nbsp;
this bearer token. C is correct because OAuth 2.0&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:22.520 --> 00:25:29.520
enables access delegation, as we covered in the&nbsp;
previous quiz question. And E is correct because,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:29.520 --> 00:25:34.040
instead of requiring user reauthentication&nbsp;
every time the access token expires,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:34.040 --> 00:25:40.480
a refresh token can be used to automatically&nbsp;
obtain a new access token. A is incorrect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:40.480 --> 00:25:45.520
because API keys do not expire automatically;&nbsp;
for this reason, they are considered less&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:45.520 --> 00:25:52.760
secure than tokens. D is incorrect because basic&nbsp;
authentication doesn’t use encryption. Instead,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:52.760 --> 00:25:58.240
the username and password are encoded in&nbsp;
Base64 format, which is easily reversible.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:59.160 --> 00:26:06.360
Finally, F is incorrect because API keys should&nbsp;
not be included in URLs. Instead, they should be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:14.000
included in the HTTP Authorization header, as this&nbsp;
is more secure. Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:19.120
And that’s all for this video on REST API&nbsp;
authentication. We covered four kinds:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:19.120 --> 00:26:26.400
basic authentication, bearer authentication,&nbsp;
API key authentication, and OAuth 2.0. There&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:26.400 --> 00:26:30.560
are other REST authentication methods out&nbsp;
there, but these are the four I recommend&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:30.560 --> 00:26:35.900
knowing for the CCNA exam. I hope you found&nbsp;
this video helpful. Thanks for watching.

